{"word":"δαιμόνιον","slug":"δαιμόνιον","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>δαιμόνιον</b></el> <br/><b><a href='S:Etymology'>Etym.</a> </b><a href='S:δαίμων'><el>δαίμων</el></a>\n<p/><div class='li500'><b>I. </b><i>the Deity</i>, <a href='S:Latin'>Lat.</a> <el>numen</el>, or <i>divine operation</i>, <b><a href='S:Herodotus'>Hdt.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Euripides'>Eur.</a></b>, <a href='S:et cetera'>etc.</a>: <i>a fatality</i>, <b><a href='S:Demosthenes'>Dem.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li500'><b>II. </b><i>an inferior divine being, a demon</i>, <b><a href='S:Xenophon'>Xen.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Plato'>Plat.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li750'><b>2. </b><i>a demon, evil spirit</i>, <b><a href='S:New Testament'>NTest.</a></b><p/></div>"}]}